  "prompt": "What happens to current account holders, how much money they can deposit in bank of old 500 1000 notes?",
  "response": "During the demonetization in India in November 2016, the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) and the government set specific guidelines for depositing old \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes:\n\n1. Initial deposit limits:\n- From November 10-14, 2016: \u20b910,000 per day\n- From November 15-24, 2016: \u20b95,000 per day\n- After November 24, 2016: Full amount could be deposited in bank accounts\n\n2. Deposit process:\n- Account holders could deposit old notes directly into their bank accounts\n- No limit on total deposit amount\n- Deposits above \u20b92.5 lakhs attracted scrutiny and potential tax investigation\n\n3. Withdrawal limits:\n- Initially, daily ATM withdrawal limits were set at \u20b92,000\n- Gradually increased to \u20b94,500, then \u20b910,000\n\n4. Additional requirements:\n- PAN card details required for deposits above \u20b950,000\n- Source of income had to be explained for large deposits\n\nThese rules were gradually relaxed over time, allowing full conversion of old notes into new currency through bank accounts.\n\nNote: These were the specific guidelines during the 2016 demonetization and are no longer applicable today.",
